<ul><li>Given any magic square, another magic square of the same order can be formed by interchanging the row and the column which intersect in a cell on a diagonal with the row and the column which intersect in the complementary cell (i.e. cell symmetrically opposite from the center) of the same diagonal.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-Kraitchik1953&#95;61-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kraitchik1953-61"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>61<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-RouseBall1904&#95;48-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RouseBall1904-48"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>48<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> For an even square, there are <i>n</i>/2 pairs of rows and columns that can be interchanged; thus we can obtain 2<sup><i>n</i>/2</sup> equivalent magic squares by combining such interchanges. For odd square, there are (<i>n</i>−1)/2 pairs of rows and columns that can be interchanged; and 2<sup>(<i>n</i>−1)/2</sup> equivalent magic squares obtained by combining such interchanges. Interchanging all the rows and columns rotates the square by 180 degree. In the example using a 4×4 magic square, the left square is the original square, while the right square is the new square obtained by interchanging the 1st and 4th rows and columns.</li></ul>
